sql:
SELECT model_id, metric_name, COUNT(item_id) AS item_count
FROM model_item_performance
GROUP BY model_id, metric_name;

SELECT model_id, item_id, metric_value
FROM model_item_performance
WHERE metric_name = 'accuracy';

external_knowledge:
- 'learning rate' is a hyperparameter in machine learning that controls how much to change the model in response to the estimated error each time the model weights are updated.;
- 'director' is an attribute of an item, likely referring to the director of a movie or similar media item.;
- The 'average metric value' represents the average performance of a model across different items.;
- The 'popularity score' indicates how popular an item is, possibly based on user ratings or views.

sql:
SELECT COUNT(*) 
FROM user_item_interactions 
WHERE interaction_type = 'purchase';

external_knowledge:
- 'accuracy' refers to the performance metric used to evaluate models;
- 'model_id' uniquely identifies each model;
- 'genre' refers to a category or type associated with items.

- "Top performers" refers to models with the highest metric values (performance_rank = 1);
- "More than one genre" indicates items that belong to multiple categories;
- "Significant fan engagement" means items with more than 10 user interactions.

sql:
SELECT AVG(metric_value) AS average_accuracy
FROM model_evaluation
WHERE metric_name = 'accuracy';

external_knowledge:
- 'Shining brightest' refers to models with the highest average accuracy;
- 'Total interactions' include both clicks and purchases;
- 'Similarity between items' is calculated as the average similarity score between pairs of items.

- 'blossomed into their final form' refers to models that have completed their training;
- 'adorned with their unique characteristics' refers to the hyperparameters of the models;
- 'rank in the grand garden of performance' refers to the average performance metrics of the models, with the best performers listed first.

- "completed training status" refers to models that have finished their training process;
- "average performance" is calculated as the mean of the performance metrics for each model;
- "top-performing model" is the model with the highest average performance.

- 'Top interacted item' refers to the item with the highest interaction count for each user;
- 'Highest average similarity score' refers to the item with the maximum average similarity score across all items;
- 'Top-performing item' refers to the item with the highest accuracy metric value among the top 3 models.

- 'Completed models' refers to models where the training status is 'completed';
- 'Average item popularity scores' are calculated based on the `popularity_score` of items associated with each model;
- 'At least one item with user interactions' means the model has items that have been interacted with by users.

- 'High accuracy' refers to a metric value greater than 0.5;
- 'High similarity score' refers to a total similarity score greater than 0.7;
- 'Significant number of user interactions' refers to more than 10 interactions;
- 'After the initial purchase' refers to the second level of interactions, where the first level is the purchase.

- 'blossomed to full maturity' refers to models with a training status of 'completed';
- 'average accuracy of their blooms' refers to the average accuracy of the models;
- 'ranked from the most vibrant to the least' refers to the results being ordered by average accuracy in descending order.

- "Blossom" refers to items in the database;
- "Garden bed" refers to the model;
- "Top-performing garden bed" refers to the model with the highest average performance metric;
- "Casting the longest shadow" refers to having the highest total similarity score;
- "Strength of its connections" refers to the similarity scores between items.

sql:
SELECT item_id, MAX(interaction_date) AS most_recent_interaction_date
FROM user_item_interactions
GROUP BY item_id;

external_knowledge:
- 'Blossoms' refer to items in the database;
- 'Admirers' refer to the popularity score of the items;
- 'Type of flower' refers to the genre of the items;
- 'Gardener' refers to the model associated with the item;
- 'Skill' refers to the metric value of the model performance.

- "high level of popularity" refers to a `popularity_score` greater than 8.0;
- "threshold of excellence" refers to an average `metric_value` greater than 0.7;
- "animation genres" are those where the `genres` column contains the word "Animation".

- 'accuracy' is a metric used to evaluate the performance of models, typically ranging from 0 to 1;
- 'model_id' uniquely identifies each model in the `model_evaluation` and `model_item_performance` tables;
- 'item_id' uniquely identifies each item in the `items` and `model_item_performance` tables.

- 'precision' in the context of model performance refers to the proportion of true positive predictions out of all positive predictions made by the model;
- 'top 3 models' are determined by the highest average precision within each genre;
- 'genre' refers to the category or type of the item, such as a genre of a movie or a category of a product.

- "born in the garden of innovation after 2020" refers to models created after January 1, 2020;
- "blooming with items released after 2015" refers to items released after January 1, 2015;
- "stand tall with an average accuracy greater than 70%" refers to an average metric value greater than 0.7.

sql:
SELECT model_id
FROM model_item_performance
WHERE metric_value = (SELECT MAX(metric_value) FROM model_item_performance);

SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT model_id) 
FROM model_hyperparameters 
WHERE hyperparameter_name = 'linear regularization';

SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT item_id) AS item_count
FROM model_item_performance
WHERE metric_name = 'accuracy' AND metric_value > 0.7;

SELECT MAX(metric_value) AS highest_accuracy
FROM model_performance
WHERE metric_name = 'accuracy';

SELECT MAX(attribute_value) AS latest_release_year
FROM item_attributes
WHERE attribute_name = 'release_year';
